      <section class="bk-section" id="section-beatitudes">
        <h2 class="bk-section__heading">The Beatitudes (5:1–12)</h2>

        <p>The Sermon opens not with commands but with beatitudes — declarations of blessedness. Each one describes a quality that looks weak or marginal by worldly standards (poor in spirit, mourning, meek, hungry, persecuted) and declares it blessed precisely because of what God provides. The Beatitudes are not entry requirements but descriptions: this is what Kingdom people look like.</p>

        <p>Taken together, they sketch a portrait that looks like Jesus himself. They are less a checklist than a mirror — and then a window into the life of discipleship he is about to describe.</p>

        <div class="bk-key-term">
          <span class="bk-key-term__word">Poor in Spirit</span>
          <span class="bk-key-term__original">πτωχοὶ τῷ πνεύματι (ptōchoi tō pneumati)</span>
          <span class="bk-key-term__def">Not materially poor but inwardly bankrupt — one who has no spiritual resources of their own to offer God. The opposite of the self-sufficient; the one who knows they need everything from God.</span>
        </div>
      </section>


      <section class="bk-section" id="section-antitheses">
        <h2 class="bk-section__heading">The Six Antitheses (5:21–48)</h2>

        <p>"You have heard that it was said… But I say to you." Six times Jesus sets his teaching against a received tradition, and in each case he does not relax the law but intensifies it — moving from external act to inner motive. Anger as the root of murder; lust as the root of adultery; the oath that reveals a troubled heart; retaliation and enemy-love.</p>

        <p>Jesus does not come to abolish the law but to fulfil it (<a class="ref" data-ref="Matthew 5:17">5:17</a>) — and his fulfillment makes its demands more searching, not less. The Sermon does not offer a more achievable morality; it exposes how deep the need goes.</p>

        <div class="bk-discourse">
          <span class="bk-discourse__label">Formula · <a class="ref" data-ref="Matthew 5:21">Matthew 5:21</a>–48</span>
          The six antitheses share a single structure: statement of received teaching → Jesus' counter-teaching going deeper. Murder → anger; adultery → lust; divorce → remarriage; oaths → simple yes/no; retaliation → non-resistance; love neighbor → love enemy.
        </div>
      </section>


      <section class="bk-section" id="section-piety">
        <h2 class="bk-section__heading">The Three Practices: Alms, Prayer, Fasting (6:1–18)</h2>

        <p>Jesus assumes his disciples will practice the three pillars of Jewish piety — almsgiving, prayer, and fasting. What he critiques is performing them "to be seen by others." The word he uses for hypocrite (<em>hypokritēs</em>) is Greek for an actor — one who performs for an audience.</p>

        <p>Each practice is reoriented toward the Father who sees in secret. The Lord's Prayer (6:9–13) stands at the center of this section as a model: it addresses God as Father, seeks his kingdom before personal needs, and frames forgiveness as inseparable from being forgiven.</p>

        <div class="bk-key-term">
          <span class="bk-key-term__word">Your Father who sees in secret</span>
          <span class="bk-key-term__original">ὁ Πατήρ σου ὁ βλέπων ἐν τῷ κρυπτῷ</span>
          <span class="bk-key-term__def">The governing phrase of 6:1–18. The audience for all acts of piety is not the community but God. Reward from the community is the only reward the public performer will receive; the one who practices secretly receives God's notice.</span>
        </div>
      </section>


      <section class="bk-section" id="section-treasure">
        <h2 class="bk-section__heading">Treasure, Anxiety &amp; Two Masters (6:19–34)</h2>

        <p>The Sermon's economic teaching is stark: store up treasure in heaven, not on earth; you cannot serve both God and money; do not be anxious about food and clothing. These are not instructions about financial management but about ultimate loyalty and trust.</p>

        <p>The lilies of the field and the birds of the air are not offered as naïve reassurances but as evidence of the Father's care — and invitations to live toward the Kingdom first. "Seek first the kingdom of God and his righteousness, and all these things will be added to you" (<a class="ref" data-ref="Matthew 6:33">6:33</a>) is not a formula for prosperity but a reordering of priority.</p>
      </section>


      <section class="bk-section" id="section-ending">
        <h2 class="bk-section__heading">The Two Ways (7:13–29)</h2>

        <p>The Sermon closes with a series of binary choices: two gates (narrow and wide), two trees (good fruit and bad), two kinds of disciple (those who hear and do vs. those who hear and don't). The final image — the two builders, one on rock and one on sand — presses the question that the whole Sermon has been pressing: will you act on what you have heard?</p>

        <p>The crowd's astonishment at Jesus' authority ("not as the scribes") is not merely aesthetic admiration. He has claimed the authority to interpret the law, to describe what God's kingdom looks like from the inside, and to promise eternal consequences to those who respond. The Sermon ends with a demand.</p>
      </section>


      <!-- ── DISCUSSION QUESTIONS ── -->
      <section class="bk-section" id="section-questions">
        <h2 class="bk-section__heading">Discussion Questions</h2>
        <p style="font-size:0.88rem;color:var(--color-muted);margin-bottom:1.5rem">For individual reflection or group study — hold the study-level questions in mind through the whole passage; use the section questions for closer reading.</p>

        <div class="bk-questions">
          <h3 class="bk-questions__title">Study-Level Questions</h3>
          <ol class="bk-questions__list">
            <li class="bk-question">The Sermon on the Mount describes Kingdom ethics — the kind of people that citizens of Jesus' kingdom become. Is this a higher standard than the Old Testament, a clarification of its true intent, or something else? What does your answer say about how the law relates to grace?</li>
            <li class="bk-question">Many of the Beatitudes describe conditions we would normally want to escape (mourning, meekness, persecution). How does Jesus reframe these as blessings? What does this say about the values of the Kingdom compared to the values of ordinary human culture?</li>
            <li class="bk-question">The Sermon intensifies moral demands (anger = murder, lust = adultery) in ways that make obedience seem impossible. Is it meant to show us our need for grace, or is it genuinely achievable for transformed disciples? What happens if you read it as an impossible standard versus a living description of Spirit-filled character?</li>
            <li class="bk-question">"You cannot serve both God and money" (<a class="ref" data-ref="Matthew 6:24">6:24</a>). Jesus treats money as a rival lord. What does it look like in practice to serve God rather than money? What habits form around money-as-lord without our noticing?</li>
            <li class="bk-question">The Lord's Prayer begins "Our Father… hallowed be your name, your kingdom come" — before any personal request. What does this sequence say about the proper shape of prayer? How does it compare to how you actually pray?</li>
            <li class="bk-question">The Sermon ends with two builders: the one who hears and does, and the one who hears and does not. What distinguishes genuine hearing from merely intellectual assent? What would the "rock" foundation look like in your own life?</li>
          </ol>
        </div>


        <div class="bk-ch-questions">
          <h3 class="bk-ch-questions__title">Section Questions</h3>
          <p class="bk-ch-questions__note">One or two questions for each major section of the Sermon — for journaling, group prep, or close reading.</p>
          <div class="bk-ch-grid">

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">The Beatitudes</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Matthew 5:1-12">Matt 5:1–12</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">Which Beatitude is most challenging for you personally — most foreign to your natural disposition? Which one feels like a description of where you are right now?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">Salt &amp; Light</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Matthew 5:13-16">Matt 5:13–16</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">Salt preserves and flavors; light illuminates what is hidden. What does it mean for a community to be both? How does this differ from simply being morally respectable?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">Anger</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Matthew 5:21-26">Matt 5:21–26</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">Jesus says that calling someone a fool puts you in danger of hell fire (<a class="ref" data-ref="Matthew 5:22">v. 22</a>). How does treating this as hyperbole protect you from its force? What would it look like to take it seriously?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">Lust &amp; Adultery</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Matthew 5:27-30">Matt 5:27–30</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">"If your right eye causes you to sin, tear it out" (<a class="ref" data-ref="Matthew 5:29">v. 29</a>). What kind of radical action does Jesus call for? What would this look like with the actual objects of temptation in your life?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">Love Your Enemies</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Matthew 5:43-48">Matt 5:43–48</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">"Be perfect, as your heavenly Father is perfect" (<a class="ref" data-ref="Matthew 5:48">v. 48</a>) closes the antitheses. In context, "perfect" (teleios) means complete or whole — loving without distinction, like the Father. Who specifically does Jesus ask you to love that you find hardest?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">Secret Giving</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Matthew 6:1-4">Matt 6:1–4</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">What would it look like to give in a way that you genuinely forgot about afterward (<a class="ref" data-ref="Matthew 6:3">v. 3</a>: "don't let your left hand know")? Why is self-congratulation after generosity a problem?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">The Lord's Prayer</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Matthew 6:9-13">Matt 6:9–13</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">"Forgive us our debts, as we also have forgiven our debtors" (<a class="ref" data-ref="Matthew 6:12">v. 12</a>). This is the only petition Jesus expands on afterward (vv. 14–15). Why does he emphasize this link? Is there someone you need to forgive before praying this honestly?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">Anxiety</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Matthew 6:25-34">Matt 6:25–34</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">"Do not be anxious about tomorrow" (<a class="ref" data-ref="Matthew 6:34">v. 34</a>). This command is not addressed to people without real needs. What distinguishes legitimate concern from the anxious striving Jesus critiques? What antidote does he offer?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">Judging</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Matthew 7:1-5">Matt 7:1–5</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">"Why do you see the speck in your brother's eye, but do not notice the log in your own eye?" (<a class="ref" data-ref="Matthew 7:3">v. 3</a>). What type of judging does Jesus prohibit? (He does not prohibit all discernment — see 7:6, 15–16.) What's the difference?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">Ask, Seek, Knock</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Matthew 7:7-11">Matt 7:7–11</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">"If you then, who are evil, know how to give good gifts to your children, how much more…" (<a class="ref" data-ref="Matthew 7:11">v. 11</a>). Jesus grounds prayer in the character of the Father, not in technique. Does this argument actually change how you pray? Why or why not?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">The Two Builders</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Matthew 7:24-27">Matt 7:24–27</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">Both builders hear the same words. Only the action differs. What does "building on rock" look like in practice — and what does it look like to hear these words without that foundation? Where in your life is the sand showing?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

          </div><!-- /.bk-ch-grid -->
        </div><!-- /.bk-ch-questions -->

      </section><!-- /section-questions -->


    </div><!-- /.container -->
  </main>
